## What
After the main event loop exits (the recv() loop in event_loop()), join all
captured thread handles with a timeout. Since std::thread::JoinHandle doesn't
have a native timeout, use a pattern like:

1. Drop all Senders/Receivers that the threads depend on (this unblocks
   recv() calls and causes loops to exit)
2. Join each handle with thread::JoinHandle::join()
3. If any join takes too long, use a watchdog approach:
   - Spawn a timer thread that sleeps 2 seconds
   - Use std::sync::Condvar or a channel to race join vs timeout

Simpler alternative: since we already drop the channels (causing threads to
exit), just call .join().ok() sequentially. Each thread should exit within
one poll cycle (~100ms). Total worst-case: 300ms.

## Depends On
- bd-PREV (capture JoinHandles)

